Conditional Statements:
 It provide different outcomes depending on the condition evaluated.
 Python uses indentation to identify a block.


■ 1) If Statement:
      Intepreter always check if statement.

⫸ Syntax:

if Condition:
  Statement
 or
  pass                        # In case if statement with no content, put in the pass statement to avoid getting an error.


# Code - If Statement
i)
a, b = 20, 10
if a > b:
  print("a is greater than b")

- O/P.:
a is greater than b



■ 2) If Else Statement:
      Intepreter check else statement only if "if" statement is false.

⫸ Syntax:

if (Condition):
  Statement
else:
  Statement


# Code - If Else Statement
i)
a, b = 10, 20
if (a > b):
  print("a is greater than b")
else:
  print("b is greater than a")

- O/P.:
b is greater than a



■ 3) Nested If Statement:

⫸ Syntax:

if (Condition):
  Statement
  if (Condition): 
    Statement
else:
  Statement


# Code - Nested If Statement
i)
a, b = 10, -20
if a > 0 & b > 0:
  if a > b:
    print("a is greater than b")
  else:
    print("b is greater than a")
else:
  print("Invalid Number")

- O/P.:
Invalid Number



■ 4) Elif Statement:

⫸ Syntax:

if (Condition):
  Statement
elif (Condition):
  Statement
.
.
else:
  Statement


# Code - Elif Statement
i)
a, b = 10, 20
if (a == b):
  print("a is equal to b")
elif (a > 10):
  print("a is greater than 10")
elif (b > 10):
  print("b is greater than 10")
else:
  print("Both no.s are less than 10")

- O/P.:
b is greater than 10



■ 5) Ternary Statement | Short Hand If Else Statement:

⫸ Syntax:

Statement if (Condition) else Statement


# Code - Ternary Statement 
i)
a, b = 330, 330
print("A") if a > b else print("Equal") if a == b else print("B")

- O/P.:
Equal
